  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is typically defined as a financial crime involving concealing the origins of illegally obtained money through a series of transactions. Legal definitions generally include:\n\n1. Basic elements:\n- Disguising the source of illegal funds\n- Making \"dirty\" money appear legitimate\n- Transforming criminal proceeds into seemingly legal assets\n\n2. Common legal components:\n- Intentional concealment of financial transactions\n- Knowing the funds originated from criminal activity\n- Attempting to make illegal funds appear legal\n\n3. Typical stages:\n- Placement: Initially introducing illegal funds into financial system\n- Layering: Conducting complex financial transactions to obscure origin\n- Integration: Reintroducing funds into legitimate economic channels\n\n4. Jurisdictional variations exist, but most definitions require:\n- Intentional conduct\n- Knowledge of illegal source\n- Purpose of disguising funds\n\n5. Key legal frameworks:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (US)\n- Proceeds of Crime Act (UK)\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n\nThese are general legal perspectives about money laundering definitions. For specific legal advice, consulting a qualified legal professional is recommended.",
